      <!-- ===== CARD 1 (already had background set) ===== -->
      <div class="publication-card has-bg"
           style="--card-bg: url('https://alex-youcis.github.io/An%20integral%20comparison%20of%20crystalline%20and%20de%20Rham%20cohomology.png');"
           data-status="preprint">
        <h2>An integral comparison of crystalline and de Rham cohomology</h2>
        <p><strong>Collaborators:</strong> <a href="https://abhinandan.perso.math.cnrs.fr/" class="collaborator-link">Abhinandan</a></p>
        <p class="pub-status"><strong>Status:</strong> Submitted</p>
        <p><strong>Tags:</strong> \(p\)-adic Hodge theory, prismatic \(F\)-gauges, crystalline cohomology, de Rham cohomology</p>
        <details>
          <summary>Description</summary>
          <p>In this paper we give an integral comparison between <i>twisted</i> crystalline and <i>twisted</i> de Rham cohomology, appropriately defined. This makes use of an analogue of Dwork's trick in the stacky approach to prismatic cohomology, and allows for arbitrary prismatic coefficients. In the case of the structure sheaf, this rationally recovers Berthelot--Ogus's celebrated isomorphism. Finally, we make use of this integral comparison to give a study of the relationship between torsion in crystalline and de Rham cohomology.</p>
        </details>
        <div class="links">
          <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2507.17631" class="btn">arXiv</a>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- ===== CARD 2 ===== -->
      <div class="publication-card has-bg"
           style="--card-bg: url('https://alex-youcis.github.io/Integral%20Dcrys.png');"
           data-status="preprint">
        <h2>An integral analogue of Fontaine's crystalline functor</h2>
        <p><strong>Collaborators:</strong> <a href="https://www.ms.u-tokyo.ac.jp/~naoki/" class="collaborator-link">Naoki Imai</a> and Hiroki Kato</p>
        <p class="pub-status"><strong>Status:</strong> Submitted</p>
        <p><strong>Tags:</strong> \(p\)-adic Hodge theory, prismatic \(F\)-gauges, Fontaine--Laffaille theory.</p>
        <details>
          <summary>Description</summary>
          <p>In this paper we develop an integral analogue of the functor \(D_\mathrm{crys}\), and relate it to Fontaine--Lafaille and Dieudonné theory. Notably, we show that in the Fontaine--Laffaille range \([0,p-2]\) that all the most common types of integral \(p\)-adic Hodge theoretic objects (i.e., local systems, Fontaine--Laffaille modules, prismatic \(F\)-crystals, and prismatic \(F\)-gaues) all agree. This helps clarify the sucesses of Fontaine--Laffaille theory in the Fontaine--Laffaille range and its failures outside of that range (as only in that range does it recover the 'correct', more refined, integral \(p\)-adic Hodge theory).</p>
        </details>
        <div class="links">
          <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2504.16282" class="btn">arXiv</a>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- ===== CARD 3 ===== -->
      <div class="publication-card has-bg"
           style="--card-bg: url('https://alex-youcis.github.io/BL.png');"
           data-status="preprint">
        <h2>Beauville—Laszlo gluing of algebraic spaces</h2>
        <p><strong>Collaborators:</strong> <a href="http://achinger.impan.pl/" class="collaborator-link">Piotr Achinger</a></p>
        <p class="pub-status"><strong>Status:</strong> Submitted</p>
        <p><strong>Tags:</strong> Rigid analytic geometry</p>
        <details>
          <summary>Description</summary>
          <p>We show that one may always glue a separated formal algebraic space \(\mathfrak{X}\) over \(\mathbb{Z}_p\) to a separated algebraic space \(X\) over \(\mathbb{Q}_p\) via an open embedding \(j\colon \mathfrak{X}_\eta\to X^\mathrm{an}\), resulting in an algebraic space. In fact, we show that this gluing procedure gives rise to an equivalence …</p>
        </details>
        <div class="links">
          <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2410.20500" class="btn">arXiv</a>
        </div>
      </div>

